<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="lesson3_4" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Superposition and Gates</title>

<p>
Now you need to know how to calculate the outputs of gates when the 
inputs are in superposition, beyond memorizing that two H gates go into
superposition and then out again. 
</p>
<p>
This requires two pieces of knowledge:
<ul><li> How to visualize a two qubit state</li>
<li> How to calculate the outcome when inputs are in superposition</li></ul>
</p>


  <section xml:id="sec-two-qubit-visual">
    <title>Visualizing two-qubit state</title>

    <p> 
      As we learned before, the horizontal line divides between two different
      possible outcomes. If there is no line, then two different qubits are being
      represented.
    </p>

    <!-- <image source="VisualRep_one_vs_two_qubits_OLD.png" width="40%" /> -->
    <image source="VisualRep_one_vs_two_qubits.png" width="50%" />

    <!--
    <sidebyside widths="35% 15% 15% 35%" valign="top">
